  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Blue Invocation to the Big Dipper
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Three Pure Ones dwell above, silently turning the wheel of creation. The Big Dipper stands at the center, truly holding the voice of heaven itself. With the devotion of an ant, I dare to seek your sublime grace.

    I reflect upon the past: when our great ancestor lay in prolonged illness, treacherous ministers schemed with the young heir to usurp the throne. I acted only to preserve life itself, and in removing that threat, the state found peace. Yet from this necessary deed, a parent's heart could never find ease—a sorrow that has clung to my breast all these years.

    Even after his passing, this weight returns. How can I not grieve? The foundation we laid was not easily won; how then can we not tremble in guarding it? I cling to sincerity and place all trust in your aid.

    I bare my heart before you, the radiant one on high. Forgive my failings, overlook my shortcomings, and grant your compassion to this unadorned sincerity. Let my ancestors escape their trials and ascend to peace. Let all people below enjoy prosperity and blessing. Protect my house in perpetuity, that every fortune may come to us.
  footnotes:
    - This is a prayer-poem addressed to Daoist celestial powers, specifically the Big Dipper, seeking divine forgiveness and protection for the author's lineage.
    - The reference to the great ancestor and the regency crisis reflects historical events in Korean court politics during the Joseon dynasty.
    - The 'three pure ones' (sanqing) refers to the highest Daoist deities in the celestial hierarchy.
